                            <comment id="486217" author="JIRAUSER19404" created="Mon, 2 Feb 2026 01:17:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Andreas,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is the expected behavior for &lt;em&gt;fallocate -z&lt;/em&gt;&#160;on filesystems that support unwritten extents (like ext4 or Lustre with ldiskfs).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As noted in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/fallocate.1.html&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;fallocate(1) man page&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;&quot;Zeroing is done within the filesystem preferably by converting the range into unwritten extents. This approach means that the specified range will not be physically zeroed out on the device.&quot;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Physical zeroing only occurs when a real write operation is later issued to those blocks. This avoids the performance hit of a full synchronous zero-out on the storage media.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the OSD layer implementation, we pass the &lt;tt&gt;FALLOC_FL_ZERO_RANGE&lt;/tt&gt; flag directly to the underlying filesystem (ext4/ldiskfs). Since the filesystem prefers metadata updates over expensive zero-filling IO, it reports the extent as &lt;tt&gt;unwritten&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="486103" author="adilger" created="Sat, 31 Jan 2026 23:50:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.whamcloud.com/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=squalfof&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;squalfof&quot;&gt;squalfof&lt;/a&gt;, I was just using &lt;tt&gt;fallocate -z -l 1M $DIR/file&lt;/tt&gt; to allocate a file quickly. When running &lt;tt&gt;filefrag -v $DIR/file&lt;/tt&gt; it is showing the space is allocated, but with &quot;unwritten&quot; extents (like a normal &lt;tt&gt;fallocate()&lt;/tt&gt; call would do), instead of normal allocated extents that are filled with zeroes:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;preformatted panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;preformattedContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre&gt;# filefrag -v /mnt/lustre/f01
Filesystem type is: bd00bd0
File size of /mnt/lustre/f01 is 1048576 (1024 blocks of 1024 bytes)
 ext:     device_logical:        physical_offset: length:  dev: flags:
   0:        0..    1023:     135904..    136927:   1024: 0000: last,unwritten,net,eof
/mnt/lustre/f01: 1 extent found
&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This seems like a bug?  Otherwise, what is the difference between &lt;tt&gt;fallocate&lt;/tt&gt; and &lt;tt&gt;fallocate -z&lt;/tt&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
